  "prompt": "How often do a Tesla's batteries need to be replaced?",
  "response": "Tesla batteries are designed to last for a significant amount of time. On average, Tesla batteries are expected to last between 300,000 to 500,000 miles, or about 15 to 20 years, depending on usage and driving conditions. This longevity typically means that most Tesla owners may never need to replace the battery during the typical lifespan of their vehicle.\n\nHowever, battery performance can degrade over time, and owners might notice a gradual reduction in range. Tesla provides an 8-year battery warranty with a varying mileage limit depending on the model, which covers battery replacement if the capacity drops below a certain threshold.\n\nRegular maintenance and proper charging habits can help maximize the lifespan of a Tesla battery.",
